snippet.textDisplay: If Mark truly believed meat alternatives were identical in taste, he would convert 100%. It's telling he says he's only reduced meat consumption (because it makes him feel good that he's "doing his part"). While these resource efficiency facts are fun to talk about in hypotheticals, it doesn't change the fact that people eat things that taste good to them. In the end, an individual even committing fully to this switch (not even Mark will do it), would likely affect the climate alarmists predictions of 2% warming over some number of years by like .0000001% (not a real estimate, but you get the idea). Does it technically improve the climate alarmists cause? Yes. Is the amount of improvement consequential? It's laughable. Let's call a spade a spade... People want to stroke their "I'm a good person, doing good thing to save the planet" ego, and strive to recruit as many more as they can to feel validated. Conventional meat tastes good, and does not consequentially harm the planet.

snippet.textDisplay: Actually I'm a bit disappointed by this video :/ As a firm believer of the scientific method, I would have assumed there would be more science behind this video. Some of the claims in the video are simply not true, e.g. that the agricultural sector is responsible for more emission than the transportation sector. Most of these claims actually feel like direct copies of the scientifically questionable 'Game changers'-documentary. Yes, there are a lot of problems with modern day agriculture, but there are a lot of other sectors which are equally or more polluting. I feel like this video is not covering the full story and drags some of the facts out of their context, which is a real bummer... I think it is a really good idea to make people think about this planet and question our current agricultural practices, but it's a pity that bad science managed to find it's way into this channel at the same time.

snippet.textDisplay:
My wife is a vegetarian. I eat meat. However, we are raising our two kids in a meat-free house. They can get meat for meals we eat outside of the house, but we only eat meat alternatives (Impossible, Beyond Meat, soy protein, Morning Star, etc.) at home. We've found that the kids actually prefer the meat alternatives to the actual meat it mimics. My kids would rather eat a soy-based veggie nugget instead of a chicken nugget.

Reprogram yourself to eat less meat, and you will thank yourself ten-fold later.

snippet.textDisplay: The thing is, we have the choice to eat meat, eggs and dairy from factory farms or we can choose to buy from farms who raise their animals out of doors on pasture. We should only be consuming animals who are eating what God intended them to eat. Cattle were not meant to eat grain. They are ruminants and should be eating grass. Chickens should be free roaming to eat grasses and bugs, etc. Pigs eat whatever and like to root. Free roaming out of doors.  Make the choice to purchase from farmers who raise the animals in this way. The more we patronize these small local farms, the more availability there will be.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't call 12.00 per pound a friction-less transition.

I'm all for a better alternative to meat. However when you look at the price of this stuff in the store in comparison to a package of burger, I simply cannot see people wanting to pick this over a package of ground beef when you need to eat. Ground beef you get WAY MORE food. Now unless things have changed...

I found an analysis saying that the average retail price for Beyond Meat burgers is $12 per pound, compared to $4 per pound for regular beef patties.
If the price drops far enough so that it is affordable I'm all for it.
